    <section class="hfy-section-card accent-red">
        <h2>Modern Realities & Open Conversations</h2>
        <p>It is easy to think that housing discrimination is a thing of the past, but modern "secret shopper" testing shows that unfair practices like neighborhood steering, hidden bias, and unequal loan requirements still create real hurdles for buyers today.</p>
        
        <div class="documentary-integration-panel">
            <div class="documentary-meta">
                <h3>The Newsday Fair Housing Testing Study</h3>
                <p>This major undercover investigation paired up homebuyers with identical credit scores and financials to see if they were treated differently by real estate agents. The results were eye-opening: buyers of color were routinely guided away from certain neighborhoods, forced to go through much stricter financial screening, and shown far fewer homes than their white counterparts.</p>
            </div>
            <div style="display: flex; justify-content: center;">
                <a href="https://www.newsday.com/long-island/real-estate/housing-discrimination-long-island-testing-1.38356199" target="_blank" class="card-action-btn">Watch The Documentary &rarr;</a>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <p>True advocate coaching means looking at these real-world tracking facts directly, providing completely open and honest data for every neighborhood, and protecting the interests of every single buyer equally.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="hfy-section-card">
        <h2>The Legacy of Restrictive Covenants</h2>
        <p>Between 1910 and 1960, developers and neighborhood associations across King and Snohomish Counties stamped explicit discriminatory clauses directly into local plat maps and property deeds. Known as racial restrictive covenants, these agreements legally blocked minority groups from purchasing, renting, or occupying residential homes across entire subdivisions.</p>
        
        <div class="evidence-image-container">
            <img src="/assets/images/ccr.jpeg" alt="Racial Restrictive Covenant Example from a Historic Seattle Deed Record">
            <div class="evidence-photo-caption">This is a real discriminatory clause, on a real property, in Seattle, that I personally came across in my regular real estate research.</div>
        </div>

        <p>The federal Fair Housing Act of 1968 rendered these provisions completely illegal and void, but the text remains embedded inside thousands of historic local land files. Pulling your title policy and seeing these terms can be an incredibly jarring experience.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="hfy-section-card accent-red">
        <h2>My Offer to the Community</h2>
        <p>You should not have to carry an active stamp of discrimination inside your home's historic public record. Washington State law provides a direct mechanism to strike this text. If you own a home locally and your historic chain of title contains a racial restrictive covenant, I am offering to manage the paperwork and filing process for you completely free of charge:</p>
        
        <ul class="bullet-feature-list">
            <li><strong>Historical Deed Research:</strong> I will pull your property’s original land records and deed files to see if a discriminatory clause is hidden in your home's past paperwork.</li>
            <li><strong>Document Preparation:</strong> I will fill out and prepare the official modification paperwork required by the county to legally clear your title record.</li>
            <li><strong>Filing & Delivery:</strong> I will coordinate a mobile notary and submit the finished files directly to the King County Recorder or Snohomish County Auditor's office at absolutely no cost to you.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <a href="https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfnLwN41kn5LUZ2IF-pFMfLLLPlaSwAQlJ7VMOdONLjhSIBwg/viewform?usp=header" target="_blank" class="card-action-btn btn-solid-red">Request a Free Deed Review</a>
    </section>

